# C++ Coding Style Guidelines

When writing or modifying C++ code, ALWAYS adhere to the following style guidelines:

## 1. Naming Conventions (snake_case)
- Use `snake_case` for ALL identifiers, including:
  - Variables (`my_variable`)
  - Functions and methods (`calculate_total()`)
  - Classes and structs (`my_class`, `data_record`)
  - Namespaces (`my_namespace`)
- This matches the C++ Standard Library and Boost conventions.
- ONLY Macros `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`.

## 2. Modern C++
- Prefer modern C++ features (C++11/14/17/20/23) over legacy C-style approaches.
- Use `auto` for type deduction when the type is obvious.
- Use smart pointers (`std::unique_ptr`, `std::shared_ptr`) instead of raw `new`/`delete`.
- Prefer `std::string` and `std::string_view` over `const char*`.
- Use range-based for loops.
- Use `<algorithm>` and `<ranges>` where applicable.

## 3. Boost Style
- Write robust, generic, and standard-library-compatible code.
- Keep headers clean and self-contained.
- Use clear and consistent indentation (typically 4 spaces).
- Place braces according to standard Boost/STL practices (usually opening brace on the same line or next line, but be consistent with the surrounding code).

## 4. Namespaces
- NEVER write code in the global namespace (except for the `main()` function).
- All project code MUST be wrapped in the `om` namespace or its nested namespaces (e.g., `namespace om { ... }` or `namespace om::detail { ... }`).

## Example

```cpp
// ❌ BAD: Mixed cases, raw pointers, old C-style, global namespace
class MyDataProcessor {
public:
    void ProcessData(int* rawData, int size) {
        for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
            // ...
        }
    }
};

// ✅ GOOD: snake_case, modern C++, Boost-like style, om namespace
namespace om {

class my_data_processor {
public:
    void process_data(std::span<const int> raw_data) {
        for (const auto& item : raw_data) {
            // ...
        }
    }
};

} // namespace om
```
